        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The line width of 4.2 km/s in MWC480 is well consistent with a typical value in protoplanatary disks, i.e., the line width of a few to several km/s. Our requested spectral resolution of 0.19 km/s is also a typical value in general observations in protoplanetary disks. Therefore, our requested spectral resolution is reasonable. 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The required spatial resolution of 0.''154 is sufficient to resolve the dead zone, because the typical size of the dead zone is predicted to be 40 AU (0.''29 at d=140pc of MWC480). 

The size of the dead zone would be 200 AU at most; thus, the maximum recoverable scale of 2'' (280 AU at d=140pc of MWC480) is reasonable. 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our main goal is to detect the dead zone in the protoplanetary disk around WMC480 via the possible optically thin CO gas of C17O. Previous observations detected C17O(J=2-1) from MWC480 with 1.66 +- 0.26 Jy km/s (Guilloteau+13). Assuming the line flux is dominant in the dead zone because of a possible overdense region, an expected line flux per beam at a spatial resolution of 0.''154 is 696 mJy. Thus, a requested sensitivity of 10 mJy results in a S/N ratio of 70, which enables to achieve our science goal.

The line width of C17O in MWC480 is known to be 4.2 km/s. Thus, requested spectral resolution of 0.16 km/s is sufficient to resolve the velocity structure of MWC480.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
