    <prp:abstract>The discoveries of `wide-orbit' exoplanets (a &gt;30 AU) by direct imaging challenge our understanding of planet formation via the core-accretion scenario and their dynamical evolution. Thus, the formation mechanism of wide-orbit planets is still unclear, e.g., the core-accretion scenario or disk instability or planet-planet scattering. In an effort to disentangle this problem, we propose dust continuum &amp; CO line emission observations of a well known Herbig Ae object MWC 480 at band 6 (1.3 mm) with a spatial resolution of 0.$''$1. Our goal is to firmly detect the dead zone where is an overdense region of the gas and dust grains. Because such an overdense region may represent a first step in the formation of planetary cores, identifying and characterizing the dead zone is clearly important to understand planet formation at wide-orbit. If we detect any dead zones with a size of tens of AU, our proposed observations would indicate wide-orbit planets may form at wide-orbit instead of planet-planet scattering. Conversely, In the event of a non-detection of any dead zones in the disk of MWC~480, our observations may suggest MRI is dominant in the entire disk.
</prp:abstract>
